    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-08-11T07:35:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-08-11T07:35:00-05:00" n="272"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d272">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.24/233: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Iran</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dreyfus</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tehran</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-11T16:00:00+03:25"
                            >August 11, 1942—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 12—11:13 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>257. Department’s 205–6 and 7, August 8. I have discussed question of American
                    advisers with Prime Minister along lines suggested by Department. Qavam assured
                    me he strongly favors employment of American advisers who will be given
                    wholehearted support by him and his Government. He said he appreciated necessity
                    appointment of strong and cooperative Finance and Food Ministers and hence has
                    already appointed an especially capable man to former post. (I understand
                    Taqizadeh who is in London has not yet accepted the post). Qavam was delighted
                    with suggested appointment of Millspaugh but stressed he would have less broad
                    powers than on previous mission due to present democratic form of government. I
                    personally am of opinion that Department has executed a grand <hi rend="italic"
                        >coup</hi> in Millspaugh appointment which will have most favorable
                    repercussions here. Qavam was also pleased with appointment of Sheridan.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dreyfus</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
